{"questionId":"33386851","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Another data scientist, Cecilia, develops a third model for the Canadian population.</p>\n<p>In this model, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>62</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math> represents the millions of people in Canada <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> years after the year <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2000</mn></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>100</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use Cecilia’s model to predict the population of Canada in the year <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2100</mn></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>54</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6094</mn><mo>…</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>54</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math> million&nbsp; OR&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>54</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>600</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>000</mn></math><em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"33386851","referenceCode":"24N.2.AHL.TZ0.10d","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Use Cecilia’s model to predict the population of Canada in the year 2100.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.2—Functions, notation domain, range and inverse as reflection"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}